@joel-costigliola 
I noticed that currently `org.assertj.core.api.AbstractObjectArrayAssert#startsWith` and similar methods say

`@throws IllegalArgumentException if the given argument is an empty array.`

while in fact they do throw `AssertError` in that case (and only if the actual is not empty).

This is also reflected in tests like here: `org.assertj.core.internal.objectarrays.ObjectArrays_assertContainsExactly_Test#should_fail_if_array_of_values_to_look_for_is_empty_and_actual_is_not`

```
  @Test
  void should_fail_if_array_of_values_to_look_for_is_empty_and_actual_is_not() {
    assertThatExceptionOfType(AssertionError.class).isThrownBy(() -> arrays.assertContainsExactly(someInfo(), actual, array()));
  }
```

Should I update the javadocs accordingly? Or create a separate issue for this discrepancy?
